bike-share data exploration¶

by rey sleiman sawan

preliminary wrangling¶

Over the last couple of years, mobility services have grown exponentially. From ride sharing services like Uber and Lyft, to car pooling services, all the way down to bike and scooter sharing services that have cluttered the streets and aggrevated many. The quick adoption and high demand of these services has left some serious systemic issues go unchecked and unanswered for. Uber's recent missteps is a prime example of the nascency of legislature and securities of these services, and the chaos that ensues when these services are abused.

For this project, I chose to explore Ford Go-Bike's bike sharing data for San Fransisco. The data I've decided to look at spans from mid 2017 through to mid 2020. While this project will leave me far from finding a solution for these systemic issues, it will help me gain a deeper understanding of trends and patterns in its use in San Fransisco. Hopefully getting me closer to understanding what has caused the exponential adoption of these services.

To run this investigation and gather meaningful insights, we will need to gather, assess, clean, and analyze the datasets provided to us by Lyft - Ford Go-Bike's partner. This will help us perform a clean and accurate analysis of the data.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Upon cleaning the data we are left with a data frame that is comprised of 5,123,984 entries and 15 columns. These are the resulting columns:

  • duration_sec: how long was the bike rented for in seconds?
  • start_time: when was the bike picked up?
  • end_time: when was the bike returned?
  • start_station_id
  • start_station_name
  • start_station_latitude
  • start_station_longitude
  • end_station_id
  • end_station_name
  • end_station_latitude
  • end_station_longitude
  • user_type: were they a subscriber? or a first time user?
  • year
  • month
  • weekday

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset? What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

As mentioned in the opening statement, I'm particularily interested in understanding what has caused the rapid adoption of bike-sharing services. While it is hard to quantify and "prove" any hypothesis without looking at competing data sets, such as train riding data, taxi data, or car purchasing trends, our data set sets us up nicely to understand where people are renting from, if they are returning users, and how long they are using the bikes for. All off which can help us categorize the type of users that are using these services, as well as hypothesize around their behaviors.

To do so, and in order to understand the relationships in our data set, we will need to analyze the data in a series of ways: univariate exploration, bivariate exploration, and multi-variate exploration. Below are the variables and relationships I'm interested in learning more about:

univariate exploration

  1. user related features: how many of the riders are subscribers?
  2. time related features: what sort of trends can we observe over time with rides taken? what can we observe about the time bikes are being used for? how has adoption changed over the years?
  3. location related features: where are bikes being rented from most?

bivariate exploration

  1. user x time features: are subscribers more likely to rent for longer periods of time?
  2. inter location features: what are the popular zones if any?
  3. user x location:
  4. inter time features: how has duration of rides shifted over time? How does this shift by month? by weekday?

multivariate exploration

  1. user type x time x location (frequency): what are the differences in frequency given the hour/month/day of week, user type, and location?
  2. user type x time x location (duration): what are the differences in duration given the hour, user type, and location?

univariate conclusions:¶

  1. user related features: the data set most definitely shows that there are more subscribers than customers.
  2. time related features: continued growth over the years with significant decreases in the colder months, and further decreases during COVID. Noticeable drop in frequency over the weekends with peaking hours during morning and evening rush hours, and majority of trips lasting up to 16 minutes.
  3. location related features: noticeable trends spiking in three key areas of San Fransisco.

bivariate exploration¶

In this section, we will be investigating the relationships between these variables to further understand their relationships, and to start building our insights and conclusions about the data.

bi-variate conclusions:¶

  1. user x time: subscriptions have grown steadily over time but have faced a recent drop over the last couple of months with one-time customer rates increasing. subscribers were more likely to use the bikes within the rush hours, indicating that their use of bike was more intentional and specific, while one-time customers were more likely to have longer durations and used the bikes less specifically throughout the day.
  2. inter location: we identified three specific areas where most of the longitudes and latitudes fell: San Fransisco, East Bay, and San Jose (as made evident by a quick google search). While all three had decent traffic, San Fransisco had the highest frequencies. East Bay and San Jose had a shocking amount of locations that were had very low frequencies! When the start and end areas were compared it was evident that the most trips happened within San Fransisco and East Bay, with fairly few trips happening between areas.
  3. location x user: While my assumption was that there would be more subscribers in the less touristic areas (East Bay and San Jose), I was proven wrong! Turns out there are more subscribers within San Fransisco compared to the other areas. This would indicate that the users are more likely to be working residents in the area.
  4. location x time: looking further into this it became more evident that the majority of uses were commute related - specifically in San Fransisco area. Here we saw that frequency dropped the most heavily over the weekends. We also saw that the most frequented times were during rush hours in all three areas. With this trend being most pronounced in the San Fransisco area, and least evident in San Jose (a more residential area). Further, we saw shorter trip durations in San Fransisco, which suggests again that the trips are more focused and specific.

multivariate exploration¶

Now that we've explored how these different variables are related, we can up the ante. In this section we will be exploring how multiple variables are inter related. From the above charts, we've observed some significant usage patterns, specifically in the city of San Fransisco area where more working professionals live or commute to. We have seen that there are clear usage trends around rush hours of the workday, and that these trips tend to be shorter in duration.

Overall, it is safe to make the assumption that there are two types of users: the working professional who has a very specific and measured use for the bike, and the leisure bike user who has a less specific use for the bike.

plt.title('Frequency of bike rental by user type, day of week, and area', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Day of Week')
plt.ylabel('User Type & Area');

Still not very conclusive data. However, it's interesting to note that the highest frequency average for one time customers in the "other" areas happened over the weekend! Further, there is substantially lower activity for Subscribers during the weekend. Supporting the idea that subscribers have very specific uses fro their bikes during the week - to commute.

multi-variate conclusions:¶

  1. user type x time x location (hours): The chart wasn't entirely conclusive. We observed some trends that would indicate that subscribers have a more specific use for the bike sharing service (typically around the rush hours of the business day). This trend was especially evident in San Fransisco, where there are more working professionals living.
  2. user type x time x location (months): This chart was very interesting since it added new insight to the one-time customer's use for bike sharing. It indicated that there was heightened frequency in the first three months of the year. When the weather is the coldest! Could this be that there are more tourists then? Or could it be people who usually walk to work resort to bike sharing in the emergencies of the cold?
  3. user type x time x location (day of week): This chart further supported our hypothesis that subscribers are working individuals that have specific uses for the bikes during the rush hours of the week. This is reflected in the sudden drop of frequency over the weekends. For one time customers, we saw what we would have expected - consistent frequencies across the whole week
  4. user type x time x location (duration): Finally, when we looked at the distribution of duration across the different cities and user types, we noticed that subscribers kept their trips short and under 16 minutes for the most part, while customers tended to use the bikes for longer.
